title: Developmental Domain 4: Cognitive Development
subject: Early Learning Guidelines: Birth to Age 3 (2012-)

document.title: Illinois Early Learning Guidelines For Children Birth to Age Three

3523B9F818064C3FB91D380B456D38A5.description:
Reminds younger peers of rules, e.g., holds hands with a
younger peer while walking outside

7A6A79CCC70147CF8330A548F84F061E.description:
Remembers and begins to apply past experiences to future
situations, e.g., walks carefully and slowly when there is snow
on the ground

B02FE9B554C243D690D71BFF053DDE3E.description:
Communicates to an adult if something is wrong, e.g., a peer is
hurt or missing

30EC96529DD84AFF89CA614226356C59.description:
Pays attention to safety rules but still needs supervision to keep
self safe

A25FF6FE4AFD49D582045E4F29B97028.description:
Imitates adults’ actions during play, e.g., tells baby doll “no
touch” when walking by the pretend stove

651587E8A17D4E17AA7BF1218F1CEDF4.description: Responds to warnings and begins to change behavior accordingly, e.g., moves away from the outlet after caregiver communicates “no”

D6DF5ADA7C0A42BFA78CF1FA9185133C.description:
Understands when “no” and “stop” is communicated through
either words or gestures

807F7014F1F34E0EB929529676EC4CB1.description:
Responds to warnings and changes in tone of voice; needs
assistance and redirection to stop unsafe behavior, e.g., looks
up after hearing a stern “no” but does not necessarily stop the
behavior or action

C9054165CFEE4441A6DFA3150E7FD34F.description:
Hesitates and demonstrates caution in new and/or changing
situations, e.g., stops crawling when reaches the edge of an
uneven surface

21B75E0005E74A98911DBDE531D1E2F5.description: Responds to cues from caregiver in uncertain and unsafe situations

18C0629E0B1B46D78154CEE097226E31.description: Actively climbs to reach for wanted objects during play

B5E9CD882E2843CA852200018DB4D626.description:
Uses social referencing to assess uncertain situations, e.g.,
looks at a caregiver for social cues as to whether or not to
proceed

DE2A648DFCB448D4A6B49D74D5520F5B.description: Demonstrates trust in caregiver(s), e.g., reaches for adult, comforted when soothed, looks for caregiver in novel situations

2C42DC507F4C4CACB99013115C1A7BC3.description: Uses physical movements to explore environment, e.g., reaching, sitting, rolling

ABA3B964808040DEBECC975765F5B3B0.description:
Demonstrates interest in own body, e.g., stares at hands,
mouths feet, pokes at belly button

4DDDF7292119441482CB6015A91971C9.description:
Signals needs through reflexes and sounds, e.g., demonstrates
rooting reflex when hungry, cries when uncomfortable

E593EBBF70D94ACEBBCDB4A0E15D93B4.description: Children demonstrate the emerging ability to recognize risky situations and respond accordingly.

659DDB26427440799BAF4E835262EC23.description:
Engages in processes to reach an outcome, e.g., mixes three
different colors of paint to see what color emerges

8278E69C717E47639CE32519E8A5DD14.description:
Draws on past experience to describe and communicate about
observations and experiences, e.g., knows what happens when
one blows on a candle, discusses what happens to snow when
the temperature is warmer

03CCA4DAE95843B490C7CB078DB755EB.description:
Identifies various attributes of objects, food, and materials, e.g.,
color, shapes, size

E2BEEE0F5A254DC9A472E08135D1295F.description:
Begins to identify characteristics of animals, e.g., “The dog
barks”

3FF8F82B09C74440885F5A7872DFCBB6.description:
Uses motion and sound to represent an observation, e.g.,
“snake, ssssss!”

3628D54832DD4BF3AC0C7C4B5F49BD9B.description:
Attempts new tasks during familiar activities, e.g., plays at the
water table, and instead of using hands, tries to use head to
make the water move

2428F8D5336B4B0288FAEC5A7D717801.description: Begins simple categorizing, e.g., cats and dogs are animals

C6DA2A04F053427AB7AE2E168E486A41.description:
Shows interest in own body; may know names for certain body
parts

D757F5E5ABC14BED8344B39E9700DD90.description: Experiments with different textures found in the outside environment, e.g., runs fingers through dirt, crumbles dry leaves

9280AA6281B54CD19FF87ABE04D54634.description:
Repeats actions that attracts his or her attention, e.g., drops
object onto floor to hear the sound it makes

7CE8A8EA6F094A05BADB5187D4745335.description:
Actively explores objects and experiences their properties
through the different senses, e.g., color, texture, weight, taste

1F66C991F4B54BEE8117AB89A9FA2AC5.description:
Uses all of his or her senses to explore and discover new things,
e.g., reaches out to touch rain or snow

EE4E3984002F46588A3D90C59C89052A.description:
Actively explores new objects found in the environment, e.g.,
mouths, pats, grasps

CB164C9910A84D71A6506B36F7C32B8B.description: Engages in social interactions with familiar adults

A482026E6846497CB43FF7B4CAF50F71.description: Observes people and objects in his or her environment

9284D3ECB45540188D08B3A1555DDB45.description: Children demonstrate a basic awareness of and use scientific concepts.

13D0A3F4267D48A6BD2FEA0078C0FDF1.description:
Uses descriptive words when communicating about others, e.g.,
“She ran fast,” “He is short,” “Look how far away I am”

24A7B6BF4E6E40A8A3B987C6EAEB8D17.description:
Assigns meaning to numbers; understands the concept of a
small number or big number, e.g., communicates “wow” when a
caregiver shares that he or she is 35 years old

9D980C7848D3442DADB9540B1A5A148A.description:
Begins to identify quantity comparison, e.g., “Which group has
more blocks?”

21A4237DFDEC4341A038DF0322375C04.description:
Begins to count objects; may count objects twice and/or skip
numbers

1F0FE00795C04E9C93BC43B6333D1450.description:
Understands progressive number order, e.g., recites the number
series to ten

E05605797E0241F19E79940042D8A97C.description:
Begins to use descriptive words for people in a more complex
fashion, e.g., “he big,” “she baby”

FCBD31EA94A143B8AABB245314A7B8AE.description:
Begins to use “one,” “two,” and “three” to identify very small
quantities without counting them

750FE45B436B4A8CACA59CE88E7C3E48.description: Uses nonverbal gestures to demonstrate understanding of quantities, e.g., holds up two fingers to express two of something

19933FF70D02428CABE340CA6B80306C.description:
Communicates amount of familiar objects, e.g., sees two apples
and says, “two”

17D15090A02C478C96B36EF9B75E67D1.description:
Begins to use number words to label quantities, even though
incorrect

4C237E0789C4400099396D1B20BFB702.description:
Begins to understand descriptive words and apply attributes
to people, e.g., points to himself when asked, “Who’s a big boy?”

F418CBC10D11413686DD5F761D793965.description:
Uses nonverbal and verbal communication to express more
complex concepts, e.g., “some,” “again,” “all done”

E809877C3A2443E896F1ACD7D238B9FE.description: Imitates counting, e.g., climbs stairs and mimics “one, two”

72A657CD84DE4BFE889FA871083E7D76.description:
Understands the concept of “more” in regard to food and play;
signs or says, “more”

00520EDFF9D14AFBA9B9214720DBCED7.description:
Holds on to more than one object at a time, e.g., grasps a rattle
in one hand, and reaches for block

2747D6014D6845CABB9AE30E031064FF.description:
Expresses desire for more through facial cues, sounds, gestures,
and actions, e.g., bangs, opens mouth, points, reaches

A4D65A62EBAA4D86AFFC0458F1550151.description:
Explores objects one at a time, e.g., mouths one toy and drops it
to grab hold of another, or drops toys in a container

AEFECB85F42B4E38B51AD425E495A5AF.description:
Uses sounds and body language to signal for more, e.g., begins
to cry when finishing a bottle of milk and is still hungry

BA192EDE86814289B19BEF322292B3BB.description: Children demonstrate awareness of quantity, counting, and numeric competencies.

6447321CBF374AF89BF329C471B81FA2.description:
Expresses cause and effect in certain situations, e.g., “I fell down
and now I have a boo-boo.”

6BAF124930AA4508A3A1107E48952424.description: Applies past experiences to new situations

567B5E4791D945DF8D2907FC291133DB.description:
Makes a prediction of what will happen next in a sequence of
events

1A27E41DC1A84A289CBE3367A82C2366.description:
Recognizes actions and objects and can generalize meaning,
e.g., sees someone opening an umbrella and can attribute that
to the fact that it may be raining

B774995C65D243D4B2B89CE0FCB888B7.description:
Begins to understand certain behaviors are related to certain
contexts, e.g., behaves differently at childcare than at home

322364FD518F4EFFB4CC01DD3D19B6CB.description:
Understands functionality of objects, e.g., mop is used to clean
the floor

B7F6078022E34B259059EF5FB69C8C4B.description:
Starts to predict the consequence of simple and familiar actions,
e.g., knows that flipping the light switch will either turn on or
turn off the light

B9CC80F593FC4DA399F930EC8CF272F9.description:
Repeats actions over and over to cause desired effect, e.g.,
dumps out a bucket and refills it with objects

702B279498EE44CC9BB6B62D79794966.description:
Imitates adult’s body language and simple actions, e.g., puts
hands on hips or pretends to brush crumbs off table

409911A5BC504BDB925399005807DE2D.description:
Uses different actions for an intended result, e.g., builds tower
with blocks and then knocks it down with his or her hand,
repeats the activity and uses his/her head to make the tower
tumble

A2D7077DEBC04A8C912EF9D5AADBA99A.description:
Attempts different ways to move an object to see what happens,
e.g., rolls a ball gently at first and then hard to see how fast and
far it will move

15731B68375A42E496EFC4C92D91F977.description:
Uses objects as they are intended, e.g., pretends to drink milk
out of a toy bottle

841FE6DEA90E4395A614308E631CB22B.description: Looks for and finds an object that has fallen

751FC1B44A5C4186847740D549C09698.description:
Repeats similar actions on different objects, e.g., shakes stuffed
animal in the same manner as a rattle to hear noise

307BA44EA3B242A898CA9DE796745843.description:
Uses nonverbal and verbal communication to generate
responses from caregiver(s), e.g., coos, reaches, laughs

F9A5B26A501347A58CC6F057543D032C.description:
Children demonstrate the ability to use knowledge, previous experiences, and trial and error to make sense of and
impact their world.

62689705CCD94D8F9F381247F9FAC0DC.description: Plays dress-up and invites caregiver(s) to play along

D65E272E576C443BBC6D81B1601B5602.description:
Uses imaginary play to cope with fears, e.g., puts monster in a
closet

91E53F3438F44981B7A076F83285C8C8.description:
Builds increasingly complex structures and expands upon them,
e.g., uses smaller blocks to build taller towers, lines up materials
and adds other components to create a “road” leading up to the
tower

157B0E750B3743CC8B9C2299EA2B74D7.description:
Identifies and discusses characters that are meaningful to him
and her

C8090B6A749A4F5581FF5A910B0CC2D2.description:
Selects movements that reflect mood, e.g., jumps up and down
when excited

E7B8A810FF1C410FBEC3C7067980E4D0.description:
Creates artwork; focuses and enjoys the process rather than the
final product

04B6CD48508A4DF5876384A4728F7ABC.description:
Enjoys breaking down what he or she has built, e.g., knocking
over a stack of blocks with his or her arm

4329B62723DD4564BD436008B10B0D1E.description:
Builds by using different objects and materials, e.g., lines up
cars, stacks small boxes

AB72E31074D246A899773FEAC4EA53AD.description: Enjoys using instruments while listening to music

C59DACB1F1C945B7B1AEFF422DB0D366.description:
Engages in more intricate pretend play, e.g., uses a toy banana
as a phone

675969A60F354FE29ACAFA5A478E5E93.description: Imitates basic movements during an activity, e.g., places beanbag on head

6ACFBFF9313540678DE0998C59800A0C.description: Engages in art activities such as coloring or finger painting

76E05745126D4BA78C3B1A50F912EE75.description: Participates in music activities by performing some accompanying hand movements

4FFC99DD9C10411DBDCAE962C4B5ACC8.description: Begins to stack large blocks with or without support

108F67F4282F43DB84BDA213A4E67CAE.description:
Begins to use symbolic play while interacting, e.g., holds a play
phone to ear and has a “conversation” with grandma

AE4739203B6348068247EFC2D52E7577.description: Enjoys familiar songs and word rhymes

7CCC4F4E4B2244A2AC9F723FB54531D0.description: Manipulates objects, e.g., turns, shakes, bangs

782CB03D6BCC4A598A4012D05B634129.description: Demonstrates interest in sounds, songs, music, and colors

3AC28E944469462F99C1EEFD39231588.description:
Participates in interactions with caregiver(s), e.g., observes,
smiles, coos

9C705885099B4945AFB493E0FB6A6D23.description: Actively explores sensory objects in the environment

F02A1AB2F4DB4A97864E09C3BEAB0221.description: Children demonstrate the ability to convey ideas and emotions through creative expression.

4E4E4BE45FAD4BEBAF79B5740F2B2930.description:
Takes on different adult roles during play and uses appropriate
mannerisms, e.g., pretends to be the teacher and speaks in a
more adult-like voice, while pretending to read a book to
students

B056606301C7403C9A90C762A6CA0FD4.description:
Projects feelings and words onto stuffed animals, e.g., “The
horse is sad”

860ED46ADF114B9A9C04F60002832D10.description:
Communicates descriptors of people or objects that are not
present, e.g., says “My mommy has blue eyes”

7DE35DFBF2804FD8AE683E7DE5B63E4E.description:
Builds in sequencing while engaged in play, e.g., beginning,
middle, and end

8FE3EF4976F94A3DA3D61B981D861FF3.description: Assigns roles to peers while engaged in imaginary play

924F12ECD62D4D2B815BD40B6873265F.description:
Communicates labels to familiar objects and/or people, e.g.,
says “dog” when seeing four-legged animals

B6391D1AA98E4FD88B7259A0CFDB7E61.description:
Identifies or names his or her drawings, e.g., points to scribble
and says, “mama and dada”

A99317E8B8DD4098B6AD5342CF385602.description:
Engages in pretend play with familiar objects and experiences,
e.g., places baby doll in stroller and pushes the stroller

CD45B52823194618A876F1CEF05D7363.description: Finds objects after they are hidden in close proximity

4693C501BC964AEBA57709609460F95E.description:
Pretends one object is really another by using substitution, e.g.,
a napkin for a baby’s diaper

B9595F90AD9F44E4AC1AC1C8E7173152.description: Recognizes familiar people and/or objects in photographs

9D973EC279E449D9900C839E3DB2C2A0.description:
Engages in simple pretend play, e.g., pretends to drink tea from
a pretend tea cup, pretends to feed baby doll with toy bottle,
uses a toy block as a phone, pretends to talk to mama

EB93BC0037394FA7B0DC287E276CEFBE.description:
Imitates adult’s actions, e.g., bangs a drum with a rattle, after
observing an adult complete the action

32A27F6AD25E49818895933DD1A63FD5.description:
Demonstrates object permanence , e.g., realizes objects and
people still exist, even when they are not physically visible

10189B49D03D46DF8CB3B95708265C21.description: Locates an object that has been partially hidden

D6686882D2AF455DBB504682983115F3.description:
Physically manipulates objects, e.g., twists and turns toys, drops
items

D46C15CB646548E3B519B5593C8475AC.description: Interacts with caregiver(s) and the environment

799CC8BBC066445BA614EA9E8E340A6D.description: Uses senses to explore objects, e.g., observes, mouths, touches

AFD776988217405F995C0765CFB73E29.description: Children demonstrate the understanding of concepts, experiences, and ideas through symbolic representation .

F40E937C4CED46B8B4320A41B26FABA7.description:
Actively uses body to change where he or she is in relation to
objects, e.g., climbs to sit on the couch

50114B93355846649E05150249310695.description:
Completes simple puzzles with less trial and error, e.g., can
match a puzzle piece to its correct slot by identifying the size
and shape by simply looking at it.

20DAAD659D774B5ABADE3825801CB167.description:
Recognizes where his or her body is in relation to objects, e.g.,
squeezing in behind a chair

0731BB0AEBEF4BFEAEE82C62CE57CD43.description: Uses words and gestures to describe size of objects

9095A6D6B6E54FE5A7080948FB7886FF.description: Begins to understand simple prepositions, e.g., under, in, behind

8258DDB1CE76469A92430EF2815F20C8.description:
Recognizes the proper direction of objects, e.g., will turn over an
upside-down cup

16B75E2DBCDA49BD874BBE290A80BF1B.description:
Uses simple trial and error to complete simple puzzles, e.g.,
matches piece, orients and attempts to turn to make a puzzle
piece fit

E417DC23C0D3412A9A27E880448ADCE0.description: Understands words that characterize size, e.g., big, small

356C7192B45D4232A649B947C44C3505.description:
Discriminates between small and large objects, e.g., uses one
hand or two hands in a variety of ways

56E63FFFCD354CA7959836819465D683.description: Drops objects such as toys and watches them move

C259FA39C2FD44EFAB5C3A255B408350.description:
Begins to identify physical obstacles and possible solutions
when moving around, e.g., crawls around a chair instead of
under it

B9B7252D550D44F0877883065614E369.description:
Puts objects in a bucket and then dumps them out; repeats this
action

0101CA85135A43B4A91ACF0745DF9C4C.description:
Focuses attention on an object in motion and follows it, e.g.,
watches a toy roll away after it falls

AE5AC5AC6CBC415ABCBB8A387DC99B5E.description:
Explores through the use of different senses, e.g., begins to
mouth and/or pat objects

B63C4E6A3E00459BB84F59CAA91B8AAD.description:
Observes objects and people in the immediate environment,
e.g., looks at own hands and feet, tracks caregiver with eyes,
turns head toward sounds

7788A5103C5C4C5485E803C971484328.description: Children demonstrate an awareness of how objects and people move and fit in space.

E18BA90626FA4A6B9E30D93A5E94AD89.description:
Translates past knowledge to new experiences, e.g., recalls a
trip to the dentist, and narrates and acts out each step of the
experience on a peer during play

8A1724C9630241F8AB0DEC8736A4859F.description:
Uses play to communicate about previous events or experiences,
including the sequence of events that took place, e.g., a friend’s
birthday party

215A84865FAA4D8E9DB8FF8092F7252E.description:
Carries out routines independently without being reminded what
comes next in the daily routine.

6EF181B309CF40E5BA5DBF44BDABB74C.description: Shares with adult what happened in school that day

06A85D00CAF54E439CB57D49B2018ABB.description: Searches for objects in different places

BDE4112C17444A47B0B6FA9CA95E2B67.description:
Recalls an event in the past, e.g., a special visitor, or a friend’s
birthday party

9E4A57B2EA5B40F0957F2BC00AA84B9E.description:
Remembers several steps in familiar routines and carries out
these routines with little or no prompting

01F9D86AA03F485184E785072D6C2FBF.description:
Anticipates what event comes next in his or her daily routine,
e.g., sits down for a morning snack after a music activity

4315A9CCFBCC48FAAAAF84B2892600E2.description:
Searches for objects in their usual location, e.g., finds their
favorite book on the bookshelf

DD9266F3E1754DE0837EC0F68622FD60.description:
Shows awareness of non-present, familiar adults, e.g., while in
childcare, asks for mom and dad throughout the day

74581F00E9164D369E56884165ABD12D.description:
Finds hidden objects, e.g., lifts a blanket to uncover a toy after
seeing the caregiver hide it

5E13CF1322F645E086587FBC9289E49E.description:
Remembers that objects and people still exist even when they
are no longer physically present, e.g., looks around for parent
when parent leaves the room

1764450925D54ED3AACFB7FAFFEC539A.description: Finds an object that it is partially hidden

2F2A1E0383824D2CA59CA3757C5885AE.description:
Anticipates familiar events, e.g., reaches for bottle and brings to
mouth

DD8BE2E6AA9A4AE681B34608B153BC50.description: Turns toward familiar voices, sounds, and/or objects

60CFE3932737468E83438338DDCF21B6.description: Children demonstrate the ability to acquire, store, recall, and apply past experiences.

E5C6A130BBB04614B8C9910CB0EE4978.description:
Identifies categories, e.g., able to point out all the animals within
a picture even with different types of objects represented

9E52BD192AD443829017D3739CDE2D8F.description:
Purposefully arranges similar objects, e.g., divides plastic blocks
into a red group, a blue group, and a yellow group

C0DD453F3C0143E9B606AEC31C166E7A.description:
Uses symbolic representation during play, e.g., grabs a hair
brush and uses it as a telephone

7AB3B3E189624898ABA7B4B3FBA5EC8A.description:
Begins to arrange objects in a line, e.g., lines up toy cars, one
after the other

3FEAEAF1F9594E1597BC685CCB17B7A0.description:
Identifies characteristics of objects and people when named,
e.g., colors

54E9C265C38041D0959C466AA90339C1.description:
With assistance, groups a few objects by similar characteristics,
e.g., color, shape, or size

22611BAB02434005ACE69715FD07E177.description: Begins to identify characteristics of the object, e.g., “red ball”

6CC6F17A6F0E4172B82C9E68BBD3C4E3.description:
Uses an object to represent another during play, e.g., uses block
as a phone

AB7B67755D5E409CBDA515A10BBB412A.description: Begins to identify and name objects and people

CA68041837504299B4D4993BAC5931CA.description:
Pretends to use objects in their intended manner, e.g., holds a
play phone to ear and engages in a conversation by babbling

75D7939E57EC4E93ACEF943CABD0E721.description:
Focuses attention on objects, people, and sounds for increasing
amounts of time

0E7C6970EE3C4AEA8F4D6A2FE8F6DB3F.description:
Identifies and indicates objects and people in pictures, e.g.,
points

243DD084A361464DBD95DF57741A3024.description:
Uses physical actions while exploring objects, e.g., rolls a ball
back and forth on the floor, purposefully throws object repeatedly onto floor to be picked up

99D68C1156654E279236A486FC07F85E.description:
Develops object permanence, aware that an object still exists
even when it is not physically visible, e.g., pulls the blanket off
the pacifier, cries when caregiver leaves the room

451E9AE16A5249E2BE9805418FF4B074.description: Focuses and begins to distinguish between familiar and unfamiliar objects, sounds, and people

AC03A8B00111466FBB3959B89F830AC3.description:
Attempts to repeat an action, e.g., pats the table and tries to pat
it again

37D070FE50404DE89F509588F07C0E8F.description: Actively explores the environment through the five senses

51CA95696AB24F5A9109351482AF013E.description: Begins to focus on objects, sounds, and people

E97AF85B62204D2295C7A6AC07E599EC.description: Children demonstrate the ability to connect pieces of information in understanding objects, ideas, and relationships.
